 is toward what the specter does. These works do not speak of ghosts. Instead, they use the specter to destabilize reality by challenging the authority of human vision and historical chronology.By introducing the spectral into their work, these artists decommodify well-worn modes of representing violence and create a critical space from which to seek justice for the dead and disappeared. A Colombia-based study, Haunting without Ghosts brings powerful insight to the politics and ethics of spectral aesthetics, relevant for a variety of sociohistorical contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aArtsxMoral and ethical aspectszColombia. 0aArts, ColombianxThemes, motives. 0aArts, Colombian-Themes, motives. 0aArts-Moral and ethical aspects-Colombia. 0aPsychic trauma in art. 0aViolence in art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074528340uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32171340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477321720423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477321720/original  a978-3-11-074528-3  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK